data.content:
Your code **doesn't use `Thread.Abort`**, so it won't throw `PlatformNotSupportedException` on .NET 8. However, the raw `Thread` pattern should still be modernized since it lacks any cancellation mechanism — the likely reason `Thread.Abort` gets added later.

**Key facts for your migration:**

| | .NET Framework | .NET 8 |
|---|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | Throws `ThreadAbortException` | Throws **`PlatformNotSupportedException`** |
| Cancellation | Abort / flags | `CancellationToken` |
| Parallelism | `Thread` + `Join` | `Task` / `Parallel.ForEachAsync` |

**Recommended rewrite** using `Task` + `CancellationToken`:

```csharp
public class SimpleWorker
{
    public async Task RunBatchAsync(List<WorkItem> items, CancellationToken ct = default)
    {
        var tasks = items.Select(item => Task.Run(() => Process(item, ct), ct));
        await Task.WhenAll(tasks);
    }

    private void Process(WorkItem item, CancellationToken ct)
    {
        ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
        // simulate work
        Task.Delay(100, ct).Wait(ct);
        item.Result = ComputeResult(item.Input);
    }
}
```

**Why this is better:**
- **Cooperative cancellation** via `CancellationToken` replaces the unsafe `Thread.Abort`
- Uses the thread pool instead of spawning raw threads
- Callers cancel with `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` — no `ThreadAbortException` surprises
